---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import { SITE } from "../config";
---
<Base title="Why local-only" description="How these tools work without a server, and why that matters for your privacy.">
  <article class="seo-prose" style="padding-top:38px">
    <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-display);letter-spacing:-0.02em">Why local-only</h1>
    <p>
      Most free web tools work by uploading your file or text to a server,
      processing it there, and sending the result back. That model created
      two problems this site exists to fix: your data sits on someone else's
      machine (a compliance and privacy liability), and server costs push
      operators toward aggressive, often deceptive advertising.
    </p>
    <p>
      Every tool on {SITE.name} does the entire job inside your browser using
      JavaScript and WebAssembly. There is no processing server. You can
      verify this yourself: open your browser's developer tools, watch the
      network panel, and use any tool. After the page loads, nothing is
      transmitted.
    </p>
    <p>
      No accounts, no upload limits, no tracking cookies, no consent banner —
      because there is nothing to consent to.
    </p>
    <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-display);letter-spacing:-0.01em;font-size:1.3rem">What we do measure, exactly</h2>
    <p>
      Two things, both disclosed here. First, anonymous pageview counts via
      Cloudflare Web Analytics — a cookie-free counter that records that a
      page was visited, never who you are or what you typed into a tool.
      Second, tool pages may show one static sponsor ad from Carbon, a
      network built for developer sites that serves a single image with no
      tracking scripts, no cookies, and no ad auction. Neither ever receives
      the content you put into a tool, because that content never leaves
      your browser in the first place. You can confirm all of this in your
      browser's network panel at any time — that standing invitation is the
      whole point.
    </p>
    <p>
      If you'd rather support the site directly, the support link in the
      header goes to our donation page. Donations are what keep the premium
      ad networks and their tracker stacks permanently off this site.
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>
